  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.2963" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <dateline>19 Delahay S<hi rendition="#sup">t</hi>..,<note n="1" place="foot"
              type="editorial">
This address corresponded to the Office of the <hi rend="unknown"
              rendition="#none">Society for the Propagation of the Gospel in Foreign Parts</hi>, an Anglican missionary body nowadays known as the <hi
              rend="unknown" rendition="#none">United Society for the Propagation of the Gospel</hi>, to which Caldwell belonged.</note>
          <lb/>Westminster,<lb/>London, S.W.<lb/>5 March 1884<lb/>
        </dateline>
        <opener>My dear sir,</opener>

        <p>Your letter of the 4th Jan. addressed to me in India has reached me here. If I had been at all in India I should have been happy to endeavour to obtain for you the information you desire respecting the local varieties of the Indo-Portuguese language<note
            n="2" place="foot"
            type="editorial">Caldwell appears to have written “languages” originally, but the final “s” was later partly erased.</note> spoken on the Coromandel Coast.<note
            n="3" place="foot"
              type="editorial">Coromandel was at the time a current name for the Southeatern coast of <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.5898">India</placeName>, roughly corresponding to the coastal stretch of the modern-day state of Tamil Nadu.</note> There is a considerable number of Indo-Portuguese Christians in all the large towns on <pb
            facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/> the Coast, including especially S<hi
            rendition="#sup">
t</hi>.. Thomé, a suburb of Madras.<note n="4" place="foot" type="editorial">“S<hi
              rendition="#sup">t</hi>.. Thomé” refers to one of the earliest Portuguese settlements in Southeast India, known in Portuguese as <hi
              rend="unknown" rendition="#none">São Tomé de Meliapore</hi> and currently, in English, as <hi
              rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Mylapur</hi>/<hi rend="unknown"
              rendition="#none">Mylapore</hi>. The Portuguese settlement formed around the alleged tomb of St. Thomas and, though originally a discrete town, had by the time of this letter already been engulfed by the growing metropolis of <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.5917">Madras</placeName> (modern-day Chennai).</note> Most of these persons have ceased to speak Portuguese, but in the recently published Reprint of the Indian Census of 1881 (Vol I, p 200) – I find that 3,641 persons are entered as speaking Portuguese in the Madras Presidency.<note
            n="5" place="foot" type="editorial">The Madras Presidency, one of the major administrative divisions of British India, had at this time jurisdiction over much of South India, including territories that belong to the present-day states of Tamil Nadu, Kerala, Karnataka and Andhra Pradesh.</note> The remarks contained in that pera might be interesting to you.</p>

        <p>I do not expect to return to India till about the end of the year, but the best suggestion I can give you is <pb
            facs="#IMG.3"
            n="3"/> that you should allow me to send your letter to a friend of mine in Madras, the Rev. D<hi
            rendition="#sup">r</hi>.. Bower<note n="6" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName>

Henry Bower</persName> (1812-1885), an Anglo-Indian missionary born in <placeName
              ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.5917">
Madras</placeName> (Chennai). He was a renowned scholar of <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.3386">Tamil</ref>, with several publications and translations to his credit.</note>, an eminent Dravidian scholar, who has, I think, some acquaintance with the Indo-Portuguese, and who at all events will be able to make the needful enquiries for you.</p>

        <p>On hearing from you in reply I shall send him your letter, accompanied by a request from myself. Unfortunately, the Indian scholar best acquainted <pb
            facs="#IMG.4" n="4"/> with Portuguese, D<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>.. Burnell,<note n="7" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName
              ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1237">Arthur Coke Burnell</persName>, who also corresponded with Schuchardt and was co-author (with Henry Yule) of the famous <hi
              rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Hobson-Jobson</hi> dictionary of Indo-English terms. Burnell died in 1882.</note> is dead.</p>
        <closer>
          <salute>I am,</salute>
          <lb/>
          <salute>Faithfully Yours,</salute>
          <lb/>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1249">R. Caldwell, Bishop</persName>. </signed>
        </closer>
      </div>
